Round 1: 
[Patient] What foods should I avoid to help manage my heart failure? 
[Educator] Limit high-sodium foods like processed meats and canned soups.

Round 2: 
[Patient] What are some heart-healthy foods I can include in my diet? 
[Educator] Try to incorporate more fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins.

Round 3: 
[Patient] Can I still enjoy soul food while managing my heart failure? 
[Educator] Yes, try to make healthier versions using less salt and more fresh ingredients.

Round 4: 
[Patient] Are there any specific foods that can help improve my heart health? 
[Educator] Foods like salmon, nuts, seeds, and leafy greens are good for heart health.

Round 5: 
[Patient] How can I make my meals more flavorful without using too much salt? 
[Educator] Use herbs, spices, lemon juice, vinegar, and garlic to add flavor without salt.

Round 6: 
[Patient] Can I still have desserts if I have heart failure? 
[Educator] Opt for fruit-based desserts or small portions of dark chocolate for a treat.

Round 7: 
[Patient] Are there any drinks I should avoid to help my heart health? 
[Educator] Limit sugary drinks like soda, sweetened tea, and energy drinks for better heart health.

Round 8: 
[Patient] Is it okay to have caffeine if I have heart failure? 
[Educator] Limit caffeine intake to moderate levels and avoid energy drinks with high caffeine content.

Round 9: 
[Patient] Can I still enjoy fried foods while managing my heart failure? 
[Educator] Try to limit fried foods and opt for baked, grilled, or steamed options instead.

Round 10: 
[Patient] How can I plan my meals to ensure I am eating heart-healthy foods? 
[Educator] Plan your meals with a variety of colorful fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins.